vectorData.altText: That's right!  The azygous vein runs vertically to the right of the vertebral column. It collects venous blood from the body wall, bilaterally.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
Posterior intercostal veins drain the posterior thoracic body wall back to the right side of the heart via the azygous venous system.
On the right side of the specimen,
trace the posterior intercostal veins back to the azygous vein and trace the azygous vein superiorly; note that it arches over the right primary bronchus.
The azygous vein drains into the superior vena cava, which returns blood to the right atrium of the heart.
On the left side of the specimen,
trace the posterior intercostal veins back to the hemiazygous and accessory hemiazygous veins. Find the connection between these veins and the azygous vein.
Venous blood from the left side of the thoracic body wall drains across the midline into the azygous vein, and from there flows superiorly into the superior vena cava.
